SIMPLE: nomenclator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nomenclator
<hw>No"men*cla`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr.
<ets>nomen</ets> name + <ets>calare</ets> to call. See <er>Name</er>,
and <er>Calendar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who calls persons or
things by their names.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In Rome, candidates for office were attended each by a
<xex>nomenclator</xex>, who informed the candidate of the names of the
persons whom they met and whose votes it was desirable to
solicit.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who gives names to things, or who settles and
adjusts the nomenclature of any art or science; also, a list or
vocabulary of technical names.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nomenclatress</ent>⟦br⟧
